references: To verify the generalizability of our framework across different languages and in the industrial field, we conducted experiments on two Chinese datasets:           LOT          and a story text dataset           Ant          , constructed based on business data from Alipay. The findings in Table                  2                were similar to those from English datasets. Interestingly, in Chinese, single-agent evaluations sometimes show better results. This might be due to the unique aspects of Chinese language and sentence structure. It indicates that for different languages, the setup and optimization of agents might need custom adjustments to achieve the best performance.

references: To assess the effectiveness of different modules in MATEval, we conducted ablation experiments on the ROC dataset, involving the removal of the feedback mechanism, omitting Q&A format explanations, and not using a multi-agent approach. Table                  3                demonstrate that the complete MATEval framework surpasses its ablated versions, confirming the significance of both feedback mechanisms, explanations and multi-agent methods. Specifically, this establishes the importance of our feedback mechanisms in promoting discussion consensus and enhancing relevance. It also proves that providing scoring explanations by LLMs significantly enhances evaluation effectiveness.
